1
00:00:01,080 --> 00:00:02,440
Hi everyone.

2
00:00:03,280 --> 00:00:08,800
There's been a question on the channel for a while now about the device's general block diagram.

3
00:00:09,020 --> 00:00:13,260
How its main components connect to each other.

4
00:00:13,860 --> 00:00:17,720
I held off on sharing this diagram for a while for certain reasons.

5
00:00:18,060 --> 00:00:21,840
Because I needed to test many variants myself.

6
00:00:22,780 --> 00:00:27,380
And evaluate how they work together in the overall system.

7
00:00:28,380 --> 00:00:34,020
This picture shows the block diagram of the device.

8
00:00:34,900 --> 00:00:37,440
Which we'll go through now.

9
00:00:38,940 --> 00:00:45,700
I want to say this is just the variant I landed on.

10
00:00:46,400 --> 00:00:48,820
I don't want to impose it on anyone.

11
00:00:48,820 --> 00:01:00,340
Because there's some confusion among the people who talk about how these devices work.

12
00:01:01,240 --> 00:01:05,500
That doesn't mean people are lying.

13
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:13,480
It can mean one thing — there are many ways to build this device.

14
00:01:14,480 --> 00:01:21,820
That's why one person says one thing and another the opposite.

15
00:01:22,880 --> 00:01:25,120
I want to give some small advice.

16
00:01:26,680 --> 00:01:35,540
When you build devices like these, it's best to rely on your own judgment.

17
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:39,980
Run your own experiments and draw your own conclusions.

18
00:01:40,380 --> 00:01:48,700
And above all, trust your specific instruments and what actually works.

19
00:01:50,840 --> 00:01:59,900
The main component in my build of this device is our coil.

20
00:02:00,200 --> 00:02:03,240
This is the reactor where processes happen.

21
00:02:04,240 --> 00:02:22,240
If people are building devices where the processes happen in the inductor instead, then it's fair to say that this coil — which is just a pickup — can be wound any way.

22
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:23,700
Wound however.

23
00:02:24,740 --> 00:02:26,100
Even in one direction.

24
00:02:27,100 --> 00:02:33,560
Because the main process flows specifically in the inductor.

25
00:02:34,120 --> 00:02:36,240
I work on a different principle.

26
00:02:37,440 --> 00:02:44,080
So there are specific requirements for making this coil.

27
00:02:45,180 --> 00:02:51,960
I already made a video on how to do it, called "Resonator".

28
00:02:53,440 --> 00:03:00,020
Next, the second main component is the low-frequency driving generator.

29
00:03:00,940 --> 00:03:12,480
Built on the push-pull schematic — a two-arm converter that works on a ferrite core with a gap.

30
00:03:13,540 --> 00:03:18,720
From the ferrite core we have two removable windings.

31
00:03:18,720 --> 00:03:27,480
3–4 turns on one winding and about 25 turns on the second.

32
00:03:28,160 --> 00:03:36,060
This 25-turn winding connects to the main coil's cold end.

33
00:03:37,340 --> 00:03:40,760
And the whole thing forms a circuit.

34
00:03:42,340 --> 00:03:46,820
This circuit is non-resonant at low frequency.

35
00:03:46,820 --> 00:03:55,260
You can see I marked a key for the symbols on the drawing.

36
00:03:55,360 --> 00:04:01,260
P means right winding, L means left, and the asterisk means "pick this".

37
00:04:01,400 --> 00:04:14,980
These components — capacitors, windings, turn counts — need to be picked individually in practice.

38
00:04:16,700 --> 00:04:22,920
The symbols also indicate winding direction — where right, where left.

39
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:31,200
There's a certain rule I try to follow.

40
00:04:31,840 --> 00:04:38,960
Right-handed windings are for the magnetic field, left-handed for the electric field.

41
00:04:41,360 --> 00:04:54,420
There's a point that causes some confusion — how to wind a right or left winding, how to identify them.

42
00:04:56,220 --> 00:05:01,560
In particular when winding a coil — say we have a form and wire.

43
00:05:02,740 --> 00:05:08,140
Take the left hand and pinch the start of the wire.

44
00:05:09,140 --> 00:05:27,400
Now if we lead the winding with the right hand and look at the direction we're winding in — you can see this winding goes clockwise, twisting.

45
00:05:28,680 --> 00:05:32,420
We call this winding right-handed.

46
00:05:35,020 --> 00:05:56,400
If we take the wire in the left hand, pinch it too, and wind in the other direction — and now want to figure out the winding direction, we look from left to right, from the side where the wire rises up the form.

47
00:05:56,400 --> 00:06:00,860
Along the form.

48
00:06:00,860 --> 00:06:09,940
And here it's clearly counter-clockwise, meaning this is a left-handed winding.

49
00:06:12,560 --> 00:06:17,900
This converter node in practice looks like this.

50
00:06:19,880 --> 00:06:26,620
It's ferrite from an old TV's deflection unit.

51
00:06:26,620 --> 00:06:38,800
Mainly low-frequency ferrite — you can use a ferrite ring, you can use a gap, or not.

52
00:06:39,060 --> 00:06:46,620
Just that with ferrite without a gap, push-pull tuning is slightly trickier.

53
00:06:46,620 --> 00:06:57,600
But since this ferrite is split into two halves from the factory, there's no problem.

54
00:06:58,720 --> 00:07:16,060
You have to put those three removable turns on the opposite half of the core from the turns that control the transistors.

55
00:07:16,440 --> 00:07:19,820
Those 8–10 turns of the push-pull arms.

56
00:07:20,400 --> 00:07:24,500
The gap is at these points for us.

57
00:07:26,700 --> 00:07:33,440
Mandatory wound on the opposite side — an isolating transformer is formed.

58
00:07:36,160 --> 00:07:40,520
The white wire is the 25 turns.

59
00:07:41,800 --> 00:07:50,360
Here's its output, which next goes per the circuit to the cold end of our coil.

60
00:07:50,800 --> 00:07:56,480
And to the capacitor that later connects with the hot end of the coil.

61
00:07:58,000 --> 00:08:03,700
These leads go directly to the drains of the FETs.

62
00:08:05,100 --> 00:08:12,860
In the center you can see the center tap of these windings.

63
00:08:13,120 --> 00:08:18,180
It goes to plus power from the converters.

64
00:08:19,600 --> 00:08:29,720
And on the back side we have the main reservoir capacitor for push-pull power.

65
00:08:33,780 --> 00:08:37,080
Plus connects to the center tap.

66
00:08:37,240 --> 00:08:42,940
And this wire to minus goes to the transistor sources.

67
00:08:42,940 --> 00:08:47,920
That's basically the power wire.

68
00:08:52,820 --> 00:09:01,400
The question comes up — why did we connect this coil in series with the 25 turns?

69
00:09:02,180 --> 00:09:21,020
It's done so that in the series tank circuit formed by the inductor and these three turns, we don't just get sine oscillations at some frequency, but amplitude-modulated ones.

70
00:09:21,020 --> 00:09:24,980
Amplitude-modulated.

71
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:34,020
If you put a probe at this point, with correct tuning you'll see the carrier signal is modulated.

72
00:09:34,020 --> 00:09:42,900
You can see either fish modulated to zero, or partial modulation.

73
00:09:43,080 --> 00:09:51,460
But modulation in the inductor circuit should be no less than 50% amplitude.

74
00:09:52,080 --> 00:09:59,440
For the same reason, the converter supply is 24 V instead of 12.

75
00:09:59,960 --> 00:10:11,420
This raised supply reduces the turn count on the converter winding.

76
00:10:11,640 --> 00:10:15,440
The turn count goes down.

77
00:10:16,520 --> 00:10:34,340
From the 25 turns of the left winding (also marked with an asterisk), you pick the turn count until the active voltage applied in series in this circuit causes amplitude modulations of the carrier signal in the inductor.

78
00:10:34,340 --> 00:10:40,780
To show up.

79
00:10:42,120 --> 00:10:47,800
Without those modulations in the inductor, the system can't be started.

80
00:10:48,760 --> 00:11:05,780
You may have noticed I use two power supplies in series with 12 V each instead of a single 24 V supply for the converter.

81
00:11:05,880 --> 00:11:15,240
I use Navigator-brand power supplies with 5 A output at 12.5 V.

82
00:11:16,240 --> 00:11:25,880
The power supplies are designed to keep the system running in autonomous mode once it reaches nominal power.

83
00:11:26,740 --> 00:11:34,440
This way of wiring the power supplies lets the system start from a 12 V battery.

84
00:11:34,440 --> 00:11:36,400
Startup is done like this.

85
00:11:36,500 --> 00:11:39,740
First this switch closes.

86
00:11:40,340 --> 00:11:45,460
Power comes to the converter.

87
00:11:45,840 --> 00:11:54,640
Power also goes to all the control chips in these nodes.

88
00:11:55,540 --> 00:11:57,720
We've already covered the schematics of these nodes.

89
00:11:57,720 --> 00:12:11,380
And then, when the start button closes, power goes to the converter that supplies our controlled Tesla or controlled Kacher.

90
00:12:12,340 --> 00:12:26,340
With this hookup, you don't need a diode at this point to block the voltage coming from the power supply when the system runs on its own.

91
00:12:26,340 --> 00:12:32,620
This battery — with this hookup — doesn't need to be removed; it's the regular one.

92
00:12:33,300 --> 00:12:38,380
And while this switch is closed, the battery is constantly being recharged.

93
00:12:38,420 --> 00:12:48,360
To make it clearer, let me show the system being tested with the series-connected power supplies in action.

94
00:12:49,360 --> 00:12:52,900
Two 12 V power supplies.

95
00:12:52,960 --> 00:12:55,700
Starter battery.

96
00:12:57,380 --> 00:12:58,900
Here's the output.

97
00:12:59,840 --> 00:13:06,220
This is the point where the plus of the starter battery connects.

98
00:13:07,500 --> 00:13:08,860
Second output.

99
00:13:09,780 --> 00:13:16,800
This is the 24 V lead that next goes to the push-pull converter.

100
00:13:20,610 --> 00:13:27,150
Now I've connected the meter common to the minus of the battery.

101
00:13:28,130 --> 00:13:31,310
And I measure the battery voltage.

102
00:13:31,650 --> 00:13:37,670
You see it's 12.9 V.

103
00:13:38,670 --> 00:13:53,170
Now I connect the meter to the future 24 V output at this point.

104
00:13:54,130 --> 00:14:01,370
And I connect the midpoint of the two power supplies to the battery.

105
00:14:02,490 --> 00:14:15,450
You see the battery voltage, minus losses on the diodes inside the power supplies, appeared at the output of the second one.

106
00:14:16,750 --> 00:14:21,190
And the battery can be freely connected.

107
00:14:22,110 --> 00:14:24,890
That's the value we have at the output.

108
00:14:24,890 --> 00:14:30,910
And now you can see one of the LEDs on the power supply is on.

109
00:14:31,010 --> 00:14:38,310
The one whose terminal has the battery potential applied to it.

110
00:14:38,890 --> 00:14:44,190
Now I'll connect the power supplies to the mains.

111
00:14:45,210 --> 00:14:47,730
They'll start producing voltage.

112
00:14:47,730 --> 00:14:57,510
And we'll see the common output voltage of the two on the meter.

113
00:14:58,870 --> 00:15:00,590
Connect the supplies.

114
00:15:02,490 --> 00:15:05,410
You see our voltage changed.

115
00:15:05,590 --> 00:15:07,490
Became 24 V.

116
00:15:08,110 --> 00:15:09,550
Practically 25.

117
00:15:09,550 --> 00:15:19,390
And in this hookup the battery has the potential from the first power source.

118
00:15:20,390 --> 00:15:24,570
And it'll be in charge mode constantly.

119
00:15:25,570 --> 00:15:26,750
Disconnect it.

120
00:15:27,250 --> 00:15:31,830
You see a slight voltage drop.

121
00:15:32,510 --> 00:15:43,530
Because the voltage now from the battery charge is slightly higher than what the power supply can give.

122
00:15:44,810 --> 00:15:48,670
On these power supplies, output regulation is provided.

123
00:15:48,670 --> 00:15:55,550
Output voltage regulation is done within some range with trim pots.

124
00:15:56,150 --> 00:15:59,410
Here you could set 13.5 V, for example.

125
00:15:59,930 --> 00:16:04,510
And this battery will always be on charge.

126
00:16:05,630 --> 00:16:07,710
Turn off the power source.

127
00:16:10,390 --> 00:16:12,170
You see the potential drops.

128
00:16:13,510 --> 00:16:15,790
A gradual discharge happens.

129
00:16:15,790 --> 00:16:20,270
And we see the battery voltage again.

130
00:16:23,210 --> 00:16:27,490
That's how our system works.

131
00:16:27,610 --> 00:16:32,950
Using two 12 V power supplies also solves one problem.

132
00:16:33,790 --> 00:16:38,750
The problem of starting up the converter for Kacher or Tesla power.

133
00:16:40,230 --> 00:16:44,590
It needs 12 V power.

134
00:16:44,590 --> 00:16:52,450
So the battery voltage is applied directly to this converter when the button is closed.

135
00:16:52,930 --> 00:16:55,730
To start the device, we close the circuit.

136
00:16:56,110 --> 00:17:02,690
The converter ramps the voltage up to the potential needed for system operation.

137
00:17:02,830 --> 00:17:08,330
And the high-voltage system's power side starts.

138
00:17:08,710 --> 00:17:12,610
To stop the device, just open this circuit.

139
00:17:12,610 --> 00:17:25,390
When the device isn't being used, you should turn this switch off so the battery doesn't get drained by the push-pull inverter running.

140
00:17:25,510 --> 00:17:33,670
The next system block, crucial for proper operation, is this low-frequency choke.

141
00:17:34,650 --> 00:17:41,790
In the first variations of some authors' schematics we saw it, then it disappeared, supposedly unnecessary.

142
00:17:41,790 --> 00:17:46,170
This choke does two main jobs.

143
00:17:46,830 --> 00:17:58,450
First, it blocks the high-frequency component from reaching the diode bridge, the load, and then the input side of the power supplies.

144
00:17:59,070 --> 00:18:10,110
The input side has electrolytic capacitors, so if high frequency gets in there, those caps can fail outright.

145
00:18:10,110 --> 00:18:12,450
In practice they just blow.

146
00:18:13,410 --> 00:18:19,870
And the second main job is also blocking high frequency.

147
00:18:20,370 --> 00:18:20,930
But why?

148
00:18:21,710 --> 00:18:26,510
High frequency should work exclusively in this circuit.

149
00:18:27,010 --> 00:18:33,510
If it goes further, the path length increases and the system unbalances.

150
00:18:33,650 --> 00:18:36,090
Starting it then would be hopeless.

151
00:18:36,090 --> 00:18:42,070
This is one of the most critical parts — you can't skip it under any conditions.

152
00:18:42,750 --> 00:18:53,430
It can be made on any low-frequency ferrite ring, or you can use the same TV deflection ferrite from old TVs.

153
00:18:53,430 --> 00:18:56,390
In practice it looks like this.

154
00:18:56,690 --> 00:19:00,690
You can see right away the winding is done with two wires.

155
00:19:00,870 --> 00:19:11,430
The turn count is 8–15, but an average of about 10 turns is enough to reliably block the HF component.

156
00:19:13,630 --> 00:19:17,450
Next, after the choke, we have the diode bridge.

157
00:19:17,450 --> 00:19:23,430
The diodes used are fast or ultrafast.

158
00:19:24,090 --> 00:19:30,690
You can also use Schottky diodes rated 400 to 600 V.

159
00:19:30,790 --> 00:19:32,590
That's plenty.

160
00:19:34,170 --> 00:19:37,730
Personally I use diodes in this housing.

161
00:19:38,310 --> 00:19:45,630
This housing has two diodes connected back-to-back, joined at the cathodes.

162
00:19:45,630 --> 00:19:48,730
The center pin is the cathode.

163
00:19:49,050 --> 00:20:00,910
Since there are two diodes in this housing, I use them in parallel, which increases the overall current rating of the pair.

164
00:20:01,730 --> 00:20:06,490
The diodes go on a heat sink for good cooling.

165
00:20:07,090 --> 00:20:10,350
This heat sink is overkill, of course.

166
00:20:10,470 --> 00:20:12,710
It's just what I had — you can use a smaller one.

167
00:20:12,710 --> 00:20:17,610
The diodes screw to the heat sink through an insulating pad.

168
00:20:18,310 --> 00:20:19,850
I use mica.

169
00:20:21,490 --> 00:20:28,250
After which, the rectified voltage hits the main reservoir capacitor.

170
00:20:28,830 --> 00:20:31,990
I used a 25 µF 400 V cap.

171
00:20:32,610 --> 00:20:43,450
After which the rectified voltage reaches the load and also the input of the power supplies.

172
00:20:44,430 --> 00:20:52,110
The polarity applied to the power supply inputs doesn't matter, since they have a diode bridge on the input side.

173
00:20:52,910 --> 00:20:57,790
Which means polarity reversal doesn't matter.

174
00:20:58,490 --> 00:21:00,410
You can apply any polarity.

175
00:21:00,410 --> 00:21:13,210
You can use incandescent lamps, heating elements, irons, all kinds of heating devices as the load.

176
00:21:13,850 --> 00:21:20,810
Doesn't matter, as long as it can work from DC.

177
00:21:20,810 --> 00:21:31,350
A lot of modern devices that use this kind of converter on the input side will work too.

178
00:21:32,350 --> 00:21:39,730
You can't connect old devices that have a transformer on the input side instead of these converters.

179
00:21:40,830 --> 00:21:43,590
Its input will burn out from DC.

180
00:21:43,590 --> 00:21:52,930
And you can't connect devices that have asynchronous or synchronous motors at the input.

181
00:21:53,130 --> 00:22:02,770
Those motors will just sit in a non-working state, the winding will overheat, and they'll fail too.

182
00:22:03,410 --> 00:22:08,030
DC high-voltage motors work great here.

183
00:22:09,030 --> 00:22:18,370
The whole block — choke, diode bridge, and main reservoir cap — fits in one shared box.

184
00:22:19,410 --> 00:22:22,010
You can see the top cover of its enclosure.

185
00:22:22,950 --> 00:22:27,270
And the lead switching is done on the external terminal block.

186
00:22:28,890 --> 00:22:35,570
This kind of mounting is very convenient when working on a board.

187
00:22:36,570 --> 00:22:40,230
Now some build details.

188
00:22:42,530 --> 00:22:57,310
The antenna that radiates our coil along with the inductor with an electric field is made exclusively of aluminum.

189
00:22:58,290 --> 00:23:03,670
For the ferrite rod we only use low-frequency ferrite.

190
00:23:03,670 --> 00:23:12,550
By the way, you can use not just this kind of ferrite rod — you can use rings or half-rings.

191
00:23:13,430 --> 00:23:16,830
The main requirement is that the ferrite is low-frequency.

192
00:23:17,530 --> 00:23:35,330
And especially if we're working with a Kacher-based system — I didn't draw it for nothing — the ferrite filter is in the reverse-turn zone of our coil.

193
00:23:36,210 --> 00:23:37,590
Near its thick part.

194
00:23:38,170 --> 00:23:40,110
An interesting effect happens.

195
00:23:40,630 --> 00:23:47,870
The magnetic field from this coil induces on the ferrite and modulates the Kacher.

196
00:23:47,870 --> 00:23:52,730
Its output also acquires amplitude modulation.

197
00:23:53,310 --> 00:24:03,110
In general, in this build, the amplitude modulations and their phase combinations are crucial for it to run right.

198
00:24:06,060 --> 00:24:14,720
About what's better — controlled Tesla or controlled Kacher.

199
00:24:14,720 --> 00:24:29,020
From practice I'll say this system works a lot easier when the high-voltage side is a controlled Kacher, which is a self-oscillator.

200
00:24:30,800 --> 00:24:33,220
There's an interesting feature.

201
00:24:34,060 --> 00:24:39,120
The magnetic field from the inductor induces electric potential on this antenna.

202
00:24:39,120 --> 00:24:51,540
And it reaches through the coil to the base of the control transistor that drives the Tesla transformer's primary coil.

203
00:24:51,920 --> 00:24:59,920
That way, the magnetic field does some phase tuning and synchronization of the two generators.

204
00:24:59,920 --> 00:25:10,720
You can also see, marked on the schematic, that for this generator the duty cycle is crucial during tuning.

205
00:25:10,880 --> 00:25:13,340
It has to be tuned.

206
00:25:14,500 --> 00:25:17,500
And plus the synchronization.

207
00:25:17,960 --> 00:25:19,920
Marked with the letter S on the schematic.

208
00:25:20,300 --> 00:25:25,860
The sync is between the primary and secondary generator.

209
00:25:25,860 --> 00:25:30,900
It's done with trim pots.

210
00:25:31,860 --> 00:25:36,540
But in general, this tuning isn't quite enough.

211
00:25:36,680 --> 00:25:41,880
It's pretty rough tuning by trim pot.

212
00:25:42,020 --> 00:25:52,600
So a power transistor in this circuit, controlling the primary winding, can do some fine tuning.

213
00:25:53,600 --> 00:26:04,140
That's exactly why starting up the system is a pretty hard task if you specifically use a controlled Tesla.

214
00:26:04,580 --> 00:26:10,020
You have to tune it very precisely for the system to start.

215
00:26:12,200 --> 00:26:21,240
You can also note that in my schematic, the grounding wire connects exclusively to this module.

216
00:26:21,240 --> 00:26:29,080
If a controlled Tesla is used, the ground wire connects directly to its cold end.

217
00:26:29,500 --> 00:26:35,520
If a controlled Kacher, then to the power transistor's emitter.

218
00:26:36,740 --> 00:26:42,440
Also, the grounding doesn't connect to the common wire at any point.

219
00:26:42,960 --> 00:26:49,240
And it doesn't connect to our coil or its inductor.

220
00:26:49,240 --> 00:27:04,640
If you connect grounding to any of these points directly, the entire interaction between the Tesla and this system stops.

221
00:27:04,880 --> 00:27:08,280
The Tesla will only interact with itself.

222
00:27:08,840 --> 00:27:17,540
The equivalent circuit would be if you connected the ground wire directly to the antenna.

223
00:27:18,540 --> 00:27:23,660
The Tesla wouldn't influence this system at all, and the system would never start.

224
00:27:24,480 --> 00:27:31,700
At best, in that case, you can connect grounding through a fast diode.

225
00:27:33,320 --> 00:27:43,980
That can help if you connect the diode toward ground from the coil's inductor — make it work on half a cycle.

226
00:27:43,980 --> 00:27:53,460
And the diode polarity needs to be such that it doesn't cut off the half-period the Tesla uses.

227
00:27:54,420 --> 00:27:56,540
This is critical.

228
00:27:58,120 --> 00:28:07,860
This absence of grounding connection to the coil works in the case I'm dealing with.

229
00:28:07,860 --> 00:28:29,000
Because if people use other tuning variants where the grounding wire is what puts the coil in half-wave — that is, they get a quarter wave in this coil

230
00:28:29,120 --> 00:28:32,160
and a quarter wave fits in the grounding length.

231
00:28:32,160 --> 00:28:39,180
Then grounding mandatorily connects to the coil to put the system in half-wave.

232
00:28:39,820 --> 00:28:48,980
But in my case I don't do this — that's exactly why I don't recommend connecting grounding at this or this point.

233
00:28:51,080 --> 00:28:56,380
This schematic is one specific case, one of the possible variants.

234
00:28:57,130 --> 00:29:08,320
You can also use a single-cycle generator instead of a two-cycle one — a parallel tank instead of a series tank circuit.

235
00:29:08,900 --> 00:29:21,380
Instead of setting the amplitude modulation point with supply voltage and conversion, you can do forced modulation of the low-frequency generator.

236
00:29:21,380 --> 00:29:32,540
There are tons of implementation options, so I'd say pick some approach and work with it independently — don't blindly copy.

237
00:29:33,280 --> 00:29:42,700
Taking this chance, I also want to thank everyone who helped me understand this system.

238
00:29:42,700 --> 00:29:51,320
And a special thanks to a guy from the realstrannik forum, a good friend of mine.

239
00:29:52,540 --> 00:29:58,080
Doesn't matter what others think of you, Slav — I know who you really are.

240
00:29:58,740 --> 00:30:00,980
Big respect and thanks for the help.
